s and standing institutions it is still too early to discern what this alternative will be it is true that there is no alternative great power willing and able to step in and assume what had been the us role the eu is americas oldest ally but it is far from being strong to lead the world in fact without active us engagement in europe an aggressively revanchist russia will step in even though its narrowlybased economy is struggling westernled anctions and falling energy prices have taken a heavy toll on russias economy but it doesnt deter putin from staging a return to global power focusing on europe and the middle east china is seen as the only power that can challenge americas leadership but it is focused mostly on consolidating domestic order and maintaining artificially high economicgrowth rates to stave off popular unrest china’s interest in regional and global institutions seems designed mostly to bolster its economy and geopolitical influence rather than to help set rules and create broadly beneficial arrangements beijing welcomed trumps leaving the transpacific partnership to expand its influence in the region but china will unlikely use its influence to restrain north korea because it needs it as a buffer state between south korea and its border despite huge influence on pakistan its reluctant to help india and pakistan reconcile india has border disputes with both china and pakistan the south china sea is also another venue of territorial disputes between china and the littoral countries thereif the us gives up on its asian allies such as the philippines south korea and taiwan those countries may have no choice but to submit themselves to beijing other us allies such as japan and india may be forced to militarise and challenge china openly thus an american withdrawal from the region could very well eventually bring on a military conflict therethe middle east with its pertual conflicts sparked by the shiasunni schism pits the shiamajority iran against the saudiled sunni coalition africa has been plagued by drought population explosion and the corrupt regimes have failed to address the socialeconomic woes that easily lead to violencethe author points out that people despite criticising the us for what it was and what it was not will one day look back with fondness the global order the america has secured they face the prospect of a world in which american leadership is likely to be less of a factor it is far from clear that they are prepared for such a world or that they will find themselves better off in it read more reply comment commented john reid jun   reports of the collapse of the eu are rather exaggerated see httpswwwtheguardiancomcommentisfreejunyearagobritainvotedleaveeuworsebothworlds read more reply comment commented william l williams jun   it will be a combination of the eu the brics the united states and japan i would hope that there would be less hubris and less exceptionalism once the unilateral power system is eliminated read more reply comment commented anthony deangelis jun   i have a hard time listening to anyone who supported gwbs foreign excursions and who was the coordinator for the future of afghanistan asking nato members to increase their share of defense spending is fair they havent been meeting their obligations the paris accord was never approved by congress companies are free to continue moving towards green energy  this author champions globalism and free trade as if it was a law of nature and not something that has both pros and cons and while globalism has created jobs in the us and foreign companies employ americans to produce goods that will be used in the us the us has a trade deficit with nearly every industrialized nation reevaluating trade policies and looking to encourage companies to employ americans is not a bad thing as for this hyperbole who will fill our shoes get real russia and china have no interest in being the worlds police the usa has squandered american wealth by inje